21L.616 | Introduction to Contemporary Hispanic Literature and Film | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=21L.616 Introduction to Contemporary Hispanic Literature and Film | prereq:one intermediate subject in spanish or permission of instructor instructors:M. Resnick term:U (Spring) textbook:Pedro Páramo (Rulfo, Juán; Continental, Editora (Editor); Barnet, Etto (Revised by))  description:Studies important 20th- and 21st-century texts and films from both Spain and Latin America. Readings include short stories, theater, the novel, and poetry, as well as some non-fiction. Students acquire skills necessary for a serious examination of literacy and cultural issues in the Spanish-speaking world. Conducted entirely in Spanish. Emphasis on active participation of students in class discussion. Same subject as 21G.716[J] 3-0-9 units. HASS-H
21L.617 | Introduction to Spanish Culture | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=21L.617 Introduction to Spanish Culture | prereq:one intermediate subject in spanish or permission of instructor instructors:M. Resnick term:Acad Year 2016-2017: U (Fall) Acad Year 2017-2018: Not offered description:Studies the major social, political, and aesthetic modes which have shaped Spanish civilization. Coordinates the study of literature, film, art, and architecture with the historical evolution of Spain. Readings and discussions focus on such topics as: the coexistence of Christians, Moors, and Jews; Imperial Spain; the First and Second Republics; and the contemporary period as background for the emergence of distinctively Spanish literary and artistic movements. Taught in Spanish.Limited to 18. Same subject as 21G.717[J] 3-0-9 units. HASS-H
21L.638 | Literature and Social Conflict: Perspectives on Modern Spain | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=21L.638 Literature and Social Conflict: Perspectives on Modern Spain | prereq:one intermediate subject in spanish or permission of instructor instructors:Staff term:U (Fall) description:Considers how major literary texts illuminate principal issues in the evolution of modern Spanish society. Emphasizes the treatment of such major questions as the exile of liberals in 1820, the concept of progress, the place of religion, urbanization, rural conservatism and changing gender roles, and the Spanish Civil War. Authors include Perez Galdos, Pardo Bazan, Unamuno, Ortega y Gasset, Salinas, Lorca, La Pasionaria, and Falcon. Taught in Spanish. Same subject as 21G.738[J] 3-0-9 units. HASS-H
21L.639 | Globalization and its Discontents: Spanish-speaking Nations | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=21L.639 Globalization and its Discontents: Spanish-speaking Nations | prereq:one intermediate subject in spanish or permission of instructor instructors:J. Terrones term:Acad Year 2016-2017: Not offered Acad Year 2017-2018: U (Spring) description:Studies new paradigms of cultural exchange that have shaped Latin America in the 20th and 21st centuries. Examines how globalization is rapidly changing the identity of peoples and cultures in Spanish-speaking nations. Spotlights debates about human rights. Materials studied include film, fiction, essay, architectural archives, music and art. Students complete a research project about a specific aspect of Hispanic culture that has been shaped by contemporary forces in the global economy. Taught in Spanish with required readings and writing in Spanish. Same subject as 21G.739[J] 3-0-9 units. HASS-H
21L.640 | The New Spain: 1977-Present | https://www.google.com.hk/?gws_rd=cr,ssl#safe=strict&q=21L.640 The New Spain: 1977-Present | prereq:one intermediate subject in spanish or permission of instructor instructors:M. Resnick term:U (Fall) textbook:Castillos de Cartón (Grandes, Almudena)  description:Deals with the vast changes in Spanish social, political and cultural life that have taken place since the death of Franco. Topics include new freedom from censorship, the re-emergence of strong movements for regional autonomy (the Basque region and Catalonia), the new cinema including Almodovar and Saura, educational reforms instituted by the socialist government, and the fiction of Carme Riera and Terenci Moix. Special emphasis on the emergence of mass media as a vehicle for expression in Spain. Considers the changes wrought by Spain's acceptance into the European Community. Materials include magazines, newspapers, films, fiction, and Amando de Miguel's Los Españoles . Taught in Spanish. Same subject as 21G.740[J] 3-0-9 units. HASS-H
21L.701 | Literary Methods | http://ocw.mit.edu/courses/literature/21l-701-literary-interpretation-literature-and-urban-experience-spring-2009 | level:Undergraduate features:Assignments (no solutions) prereq:two subjects in literature instructors:A. Bahr term:U (Spring) textbook:Eliot, T. S. The Waste Land and Other Writings. New York, NY: The Modern Library, 2002. textbook:Woolf, Virgina. Mrs. Dalloway. New York, NY: Penguin USA, 1996. textbook:Carson, Ciaran. Belfast Confetti. Winston-Salem, NC: Wake Forest University Press, 1989. textbook:Wilson, Robert McLiam. Ripley Bogle. New York, NY: Ballantine Books, 2000. textbook:Selvon, Sam. The Lonely Londoners. New York, NY: Longman, 1989.  description:Introduces practice and theory of literary criticism. Seminar focuses on topics such as the history of critical methods and techniques, and the continuity of certain subjects in literary history. Instruction and practice in oral and written communication. Previously taught topics include Virginia Woolf's Shakespeare, Theory and Use of Figurative Language, and Text, Context, Subtext, Pretext . Approved for credit in the Women's and Gender Studies when content meets requirements for subjects in that program.Limited to 12.  3-0-9 units. HASS-H
